Title: Nadar Varalaru Karuppa...? Kaviya...?
Author: R Lajapathi Roy
My Review:
The title, cover page and the controversy around the books release interested me to pick this book. I agree with one thing with the author. Simple truth is Nadars were not warriors but low caste people who didn't even have the privilege of owning an umbrella or entering a temple. Just because the caste has grown economically and are in well to do positions in the current age doesn't mean we can rewrite the history or not accept the hard truths.

As in few Tamil non-fiction books, this book too lacks enough reference to the facts it claims. The arguments presented in the book are not not two sided and it looked more towards one side.

Author: Kalki
My Review:
This is a awesome book I have read so far. Kalki has explained history in such a beautiful way. The way he explains the scenes is wonderful. I loved the whole book. I have read all his historical novels. I wish he had written few more such novels. Ponniyin Selvan is the best among all the other novels he has written. I didn’t like the ending in ‘Sivagamiyin Sabatham’. But I loved the climax in this story. After reading this story I am little bit interested in knowing the history of Tamil Nadu.

Ponniyin Selvan is a must read book for all the book readers.

My Review:
Just can't keep myself away from comparing this book to Ponniyin Selvan. Seems like the author has put more effort into making this book into a sequel to Ponniyin Selvan.

I read Ponniyin Selvan in 2010. At that point in time, I hadn't read many other books and I enjoyed it completely. Till date when people ask me for book suggestions, I used to suggest them Ponniyin Selvan.

Now after reading this book, I feel its no way close to A song of ice and fire. Now thinking back I am scared of rereading Ponniyin Selvan. It's the same thing I had for movies which I enjoyed in my childhood days. I just don't want to watch them again and spoil the feeling.

Title: ஜிப்ஸி
Author: Raju Murugan
My Review:
After picking this book for reading I chanced upon the trailer for this upcoming movie called Gypsy by the author of the book.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E5pELCDq820

You will definitely love this book if you love to travel. The book is about Gipsies, people who are nomads. He tries to get the stories of nomads from TamilNadu and how their current lives are. This is a very small book for a full-blown research text. But the author has strategically mentioned where to find more text on this subject and also people who are actively researching about them.

The book has two tracks of storytelling. One of them is authors experience in Varanasi and the other about meeting nomads across Tamil Nadu. The author has subtly argued how Buddha was the first nomad he knew to LTTE Prabhakaran is also a nomad.

Authors thoughts are towards left politics and he also mentions how he believes in God but not the nonsense around it.

It actually made me realise how less we think about people whom we meet in our everyday life. I have met almost all the nomads he has written about in my real life and I never gave a second thought about them at all.

The author sure loves to travel, music and reading. The book is filled with recommendations of music he liked and the authors and books he enjoyed. Very interesting short read.

Title: காவல் கோட்டம் [kaval kottam]
Author: S. Venkatesan
My Review:
This book is a roller coaster of sorts. There are chapters which I felt like I want to be just done with it and there are chapters which gave me goosebumps. Probably making the book a few chapters less would have made the book even better. That being said the book is still a masterpiece.

This is not the first history book I am reading. But this book is unique in the way that the author decided to present the facts. Its a work of fiction with history sprinkled in. So it's up to you to believe in what you want. That's a nice move from the author especially with authors like Perumal Murugan getting into trouble for their books.

The author made me fall in love with Madurai. How much it has changed in all these centuries. The best thing I loved about this book is how history is mostly not about the rulers of the place but about the people of the place. I can't stop comparing it with Ivory Throne the last history I book I had read which speaks all about the rulers of Travancore but very rarely about their subjects.

This book gives a lot of things to ponder upon. For instance, there is a scene where an old lady narrates to the youngsters of her village how she had asked for what's called a modern-day divorce because of her husbands impotency and how she had married thrice and found the love of her life. I don't think in today's Indian society its possible to marry thrice and live life without being looked down by others.

Be it the cover image, be it the scene where the Madurai fort is broken down the author was done some extensive research. After reading this book my look on South Tamil society is never going to be the same.

The book mentions a lot of small villages and places in and around Madurai. It would be better to arrange a Kaval Kottam tour like the already existing Ponninyin Selvan tour. Would love to know the places.

There were some words which I didn't understand. For instance the word mallu vetti. Google still is not so good in vernacular languages to give the right response to these words. So I had to move with my assumptions of meanings for that word. Have to buy a Tamil dictionary soon.

Overall the book is a must read if you want to understand the life of Mukulathor folks around Madurai. I am not from this caste and my respect for them has increased multifold after reading this book.

Title: வேருக்கு நீர் [Verukku Neer]
Author: Rajam Krishnan
My Review:
This book is a masterpiece of fictional work. The author is known for her research and political messages through her stories. This book reflects it well.

The story deals with the erosion of Gandhian values in the society. The book won Sahitya Academy award in 1973. Today in 2018, when the current generation would have never heard of Sarvodhya or completely believes in some random message about Gandhi from a piece of information shared in the social media, not everyone will enjoy the book.

The book coveys message on Gandhian values, feminism, democracy vs socialist thoughts, environmental awareness, philosophy etc. Interestingly feminism in 1973 has changed a lot from what it is today.

The book is written in a period where the first generation Gandhian politicians are almost done with their ruling and the new generation of politicians who didn't have any motive to serve the people are coming to power. The book shows the anger of a woman who follows Gandhian values all her life and also the struggle she faces with the materialistic world around her.

Title: Why I killed Gandhi: Revised Edition of Original Version (Classics to Go)
Author: Nathuram Godse
My Review:
I would like to believe myself as a Gandhian. So my review might be biased towards it.

First of all things, you can never justify killing another soul. And you just took 9 pages to justify killing a person called as Mahatma. What was I expecting when I read this book (🤦)

This book or essay is the final statement Godse made in court during his trial for the murder of Gandhi. I had heard that this essay is so convincing. One of the judges reportedly said that if the audience were the jury, they would have acquitted Godse. So I started this book with all my enthusiasm and open-mindedness humanly possible. But the book turned out to be a complete waste of time.

Gandhi was an idealist and not so pragmatic in his philosophies, this much I can agree with him. But that doesn't give anyone right to kill a person.

What worries or saddens me is people making the same kind of arguments even today and believing in this crap.

Title: Annihilation of Caste
Author: B.R. Ambedkar
My Review:
This book is the undelivered speech Ambedkar has prepared for a conference. The essay is a masterpiece. I have never highlighted so many times in such a small book. Exclude the appendix and the introduction and the main essay is well thought through. In the introduction, Ambedkar speaks about why the speech was not delivered and in the appendix, he gives his reply to Gandhi's reply to this essay.

I felt the book is bit outdated since the social-political landscape of the country has changed a lot since the book was written. Still, we have a long road to go to abolish caste from India. And sadly no current politician is speaking about this anymore. Caste has a direct correlation to the votes and I wonder if Ambedkar ever dreamt of such a day would come.

Title: Gut: The Inside Story of Our Body’s Most Underrated Organ

My Review:
Generally, when I read a medical book, I have the feeling I have all the sickness described in the book. So I avoid medical books. But this book is different.

Its written for a layman accompanied with illustrations which makes the concepts easier to understand. However, there are few sections which I was not able to grasp.

Overall its an informative and nice read.
Private Notes:
Cleaning does not mean annihilating all bacteria. Cleanliness is a healthy balance of sufficient good bacteria and a few bad ones.

Do not take antibiotics unless it is really necessary.

Every culture in the world includes traditional dishes that rely on the help of microbes for their preparation.

Title: Digital Gold: Bitcoin and the Inside Story of the Misfits and Millionaires Trying to Reinvent Money
Author: Nathaniel Popper
Private Notes:
The most fundamental rule of Bitcoin was the democratic principle that the blockchain with the most support was the official one.

Privacy in an open society requires anonymous transaction systems.

Bitcoin provides a glimpse of where we might be when the government inevitably stops printing the faces of dead presidents on expensive paper.

Title: The Education of a Value Investor: My Transformative Quest for Wealth, Wisdom, and Enlightenment
Author: Guy Spier
Private Notes:
Key takeaways:

1. Check stock prices as infrequently as possible.
2. If someone tries to sell you something, don't buy it.
3. Gather investment research in the right order.
4. If a stock tumbles after you it, don't sell it for two years. Before buying any stock, make sure you like it enough to hold on for at least two years, even if the price halves right after you buy it.

Title: Third Class in Indian Railways
Author: Mahatma Gandhi
My Review:
This book is a collection of six essays by Gandhi. They are

1. THIRD CLASS IN INDIAN RAILWAYS
2. VERNACULARS AS MEDIA OF INSTRUCTION
3. SWADESHI
4. AHIMSA
5. THE MORAL BASIS OF CO-OPERATION
6. NATIONAL DRESS

The first essay is about poverty in India, especially when Gandhi traveled in trains across India. The second essay is about the importance of Indian vernacular languages. The next three essays are about Swadeshi, Ahimsa and Co-operation. In the essay national essay he response to an author about his dressing style.

Title: Holy Cow! An Indian Adventure
Author: Sarah Macdonald
My Review:
This book throws light on the issues a foreigner faces in India. The author is an Australian. She has a good sense of humour and has an eye for the details. But at times things are exaggerated a bit to be interesting.

When I read the part in which her Indian friend explains her about the matrimony ads in newspaper, I wouldn't control my laughter. When she explains scenes, she gives more details about those scenes, which makes the book more interesting. Personally I as an Indian feels few things could never happen in India. Like the toilet cleaner offering her a hand job etc.

After reading the first few chapters, I was thinking how mean the author is to say bad things about my motherland. But the later chapters turned well. Most of things stated in the book happen in India, but not all the things which she has mentioned.

Author: Paulo Coelho

Title: The Monk Who Sold His Ferrari: A Fable About Fulfilling Your Dreams and Reaching Your Destiny
Author: Robin S. Sharma

Title: The Way of the Bow
Author: Paulo Coelho
My Review: A very short read. I read it less than two hours.Paulo explains in his own style of story telling. The story is kind of different than his normal other books. It is kind of a chinese movie in which the monk gives advice to his discipline.

Title: The Mythical Man Month: Essays on Software Engineering
Author: Frederick P. Brooks Jr.
My Review: Nice read for a Programmer/Manager

Title: Eleven Minutes
Author: Paulo Coelho

Title: My Reminiscences
Author: Rabindranath Tagore

Title: 100 Must-Read Life-Changing Books
Author: Nick Rennison
My Review: This book lists 100 good books and gives a short introduction about each book.

Title: 100 Most Disgusting Things On The Planet
Author: Anna Claybourne

Title: 500 Poses for Photographing Women: A Visual Sourcebook for Portrait Photographers
Author: Michelle Perkins
My Review:
This book doesn't teach you to pose for a photograph. It acts as a reference, you can refer to it if you need any pose ideas.

If there were some explanations given to each image it would be the best one.

Title: I have a Dream
Author: Rashmi Bansal
My Review:
Reading success stories is not always inspiring :-(
Moreover there is a lot of Hindi content in the book...It's kind of irritating for a guy who does't know Hindi...

Title: The Alchemist
Author: Paulo Coelho
My Review: The author tries a new style by giving self help books as a fable and he fails miserably..

Title: Rich Dad, Poor Dad: What the Rich Teach Their Kids About Money -- That the Poor and Middle Class Do Not!
Author: Robert T. Kiyosaki
My Review: This book made me understand how wealthy I am. The understanding of asset, liability and wealth will surely make a difference in the way you think about money.

Title: Birds, Beasts, and Bandits: 14 Days with Veerappan
Author: Krupakar
My Review:
Nice read. The author boosts himself a little bit here and there. It was interesting to read that Veerappan was a good dancer, had chance to get into hollywood etc.

Overall the book is a good read. I would prefer you to read a little bit of Veerappan before starting the book if you had not heard about him before.

Title: Why Men Want Sex And Women Need Love
Author: Allan Pease
My Review:
The title says it all, "Why men want sex and women need love". The point explained in first 6 chapters men and women behave in such a way because they are hardwired in such a way. The text becomes boring repeating the same point.

The remaining chapters are interesting but they are also so long to convey the message.

Title: Manual Of The Warrior Of Light
Author: Paulo Coelho
My Review: Was not inspiring like other Paulo books. This book is not meant to be read in a single stand. It is supposed to be used as a reference.

Title: He Swam with Sharks for an Ice-Cream
Author: Dhaval Bhatia
My Review: Biography of Dhirubhai Ambani...Had a lot of stories..Good inspirational book for budding entrepreneurs...

Title: Code Name God : The  Spiritual Odyssey of a Man of Science
Author: Mani Bhaumik
My Review:
The author Mani Bhaumik starts explaining how he ended up doing research in spirituality. He tells us his story from rags to riches. And then what made him go in search of explanation for spirituality.

The scientist explains spiritaulity with science and conlcudes that God exists. He refers to a lot of Physics theories to conclude at this point.

I felt it dificult to understand the last few chapters in which he dives deep into the theories of Physics. Other than that the book is fine.

Title: The White Tiger
Author: Aravind Adiga
My Review:
It's similar to "Slumdog Millionaire". I would recommend it to anyone who needs to understand modern day India.

The author explains both the darkness and the light of India. He explains both the rich and the poor, the village and the city.

Title: Veronika Decides To Die
Author: Paulo Coelho
My Review:
The moral of the story is "Live the life as if you are dying tomorrow". Paulo Coelho uses his own way of telling the story of a suicide attempt girl Veronika. She attempts suicide and is saved from it. She is said that she will dye within a week. Then the author captures the mind of the girl as this book.

I especially liked the part where Veronika and Zedka speaks about what is madness and who is a mad man/woman.

Title: 2 States: The Story of My Marriage
Author: Chetan Bhagat
My Review:
Loved the book.
I have never read a novel before. Just started with this book 2 States. I started reading it one Sunday morning. I missed my breakfast and lunch to just keep reading the book.

Title: Hackers & Painters: Big Ideas from the Computer Age
Author: Paul Graham
My Review: Few essays are really thought provoking. Loved them.

Title: Don't Make Me Think: A Common Sense Approach to Web Usability
Author: Steve Krug
My Review: Really enjoyed reading the book. The best thing I liked about the book is its brevity. I also loved the illustrations used. I very much loved the title after I knew the meaning of it. Will be reading the Authors next book shortly.

Title: Taj Mahal
Author: Giles Tillotson
My Review: Has a lot of historical facts about the Taj Mahal..I personally liked the black taj plan.

Title: Bangalore Tiger: How Indian Tech Upstart Wipro Is Rewriting the Rules of Global Competition
Author: Steve Hamm
My Review:
The book shows a big picture of software outsourcing in India. Why Indians leed the market and what will happen in future.

It says the whole story from Wipro's point of view but it is almost the same in all big Service Provider Organisations in India.

Title: Prepare For Ielts: Academic Practice Tests
Author: Penelope Cameron

Title: The Answers: All the office questions you never dared to ask
Author: Lucy Kellaway

Title: Myth = Mithya: A Handbook of Hindu Mythology
Author: Devdutt Pattanaik
